<tr><td></td><td>TEASER</td></tr>
<tr><td></td><td>LOCATION--Replimat</td></tr>
<tr id="L1"><td><a href="#L1">1</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Mealtime</td></tr>

<tr id="L2"><td><a href="#L2">2</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Can I interest you in some more Yigrish cream pie?</td></tr>

<tr id="L3"><td><a href="#L3">3</a></td><td>GARAK:  No, thank you, Doctor. I'm quite full.</td></tr>

<tr id="L4"><td><a href="#L4">4</a></td><td>BASHIR:  But you've hardly touched your food.</td></tr>

<tr id="L5"><td><a href="#L5">5</a></td><td>GARAK:  The truth is, I'm trying to lose a little weight. Hemming women's dresses may provide me with a modest income, but it offers very little in the way of exercise.</td></tr>

<tr id="L6"><td><a href="#L6">6</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Well if you like, I can help you set up an exercise programme in one of the holosuites here.</td></tr>

<tr id="L7"><td><a href="#L7">7</a></td><td>GARAK:  I might just take you up on that. And speaking of holosuites</td></tr>

<tr id="L8"><td><a href="#L8">8</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Garak takes out an isolinear rod with a ribbon around it and hands it to Bashir.</td></tr>

<tr id="L9"><td><a href="#L9">9</a></td><td>GARAK:  Happy birthday. I know it's a few days off, but I wanted to give you your present early. It's a Cardassian holosuite programme. An adaptation of one of Shoggoth's enigma tales.</td></tr>

<tr id="L10"><td><a href="#L10">10</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Is it? I see.</td></tr>

<tr id="L11"><td><a href="#L11">11</a></td><td>GARAK:  You sound disappointed. I thought you enjoyed mystery novels.</td></tr>

<tr id="L12"><td><a href="#L12">12</a></td><td>BASHIR:  I do. Human mystery novels. The problem with Cardassian enigma tales is that they all end the same way. All the suspects are always guilty.</td></tr>

<tr id="L13"><td><a href="#L13">13</a></td><td>GARAK:  Yes, but the challenge is determining exactly who is guilty of what. Is Lieutenant Dax throwing one of her surprise parties for you this year?</td></tr>

<tr id="L14"><td><a href="#L14">14</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Oh, so I'm told.</td></tr>

<tr id="L15"><td><a href="#L15">15</a></td><td>GARAK:  You don't sound enthusiastic about that either.</td></tr>

<tr id="L16"><td><a href="#L16">16</a></td><td>BASHIR:  It's not that I don't appreciate all the trouble she goes to and everything. It's just that this year is a little different.</td></tr>

<tr id="L17"><td><a href="#L17">17</a></td><td>GARAK:  How so?</td></tr>

<tr id="L18"><td><a href="#L18">18</a></td><td>BASHIR:  This will be my thirtieth birthday.</td></tr>

<tr id="L19"><td><a href="#L19">19</a></td><td>GARAK:  And?</td></tr>

<tr id="L20"><td><a href="#L20">20</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Well, in many human cultures, the thirtieth birthday is considered a sort of landmark. It marks the end of youth and the beginning of the slow march into middle age.</td></tr>

<tr id="L21"><td><a href="#L21">21</a></td><td>GARAK:  And that's considered bad?</td></tr>

<tr id="L22"><td><a href="#L22">22</a></td><td>BASHIR:  No. It's just that when you hit thirty, it becomes harder and harder to ignore the passage of time.</td></tr>

<tr id="L23"><td><a href="#L23">23</a></td><td>GARAK:  I wasn't aware that humans saw growing old as a negative experience. On Cardassia, advanced age is seen as a sign of power and dignity.</td></tr>

<tr id="L24"><td><a href="#L24">24</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Well I am aware that aging is part of the natural process of life. It's just that I don't want to be reminded of it, that's all. Look, Garak, in two days I turn thirty. If I choose to be grumpy about it, that's my prerogative.</td></tr>

<tr id="L25"><td><a href="#L25">25</a></td><td>GARAK:  By all means, Doctor, be as grumpy as you like.</td></tr>

<tr id="L26"><td><a href="#L26">26</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Thank you for the support.</td></tr>

<tr id="L27"><td><a href="#L27">27</a></td><td>QUARK:  Excuse me, Doctor.</td></tr>

<tr id="L28"><td><a href="#L28">28</a></td><td>BASHIR:  What? Oh, Quark. I'm sorry. How can I help you?</td></tr>

<tr id="L29"><td><a href="#L29">29</a></td><td>ANNOTATION: Quark approaches, accompanied by a large reptilian with red eyes and horns or teeth sticking out of his face.</td></tr>

<tr id="L30"><td><a href="#L30">30</a></td><td>QUARK:  Er, my friend Altovar here is looking to purchase a small quantity of er, biomemetic gel. And I was wondering if you might be able to tell him where he can find, let's say, a few hundred millilitres.</td></tr>

<tr id="L31"><td><a href="#L31">31</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Biomemetic gel is a restricted substance. Its sale is strictly prohibited by Federation law.</td></tr>

<tr id="L32"><td><a href="#L32">32</a></td><td>QUARK:  I thought so. You see, I told you.</td></tr>

<tr id="L33"><td><a href="#L33">33</a></td><td>ALTOVAR:  I'm willing to pay whatever's necessary. Name your price.</td></tr>

<tr id="L34"><td><a href="#L34">34</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Why do you need it?</td></tr>

<tr id="L35"><td><a href="#L35">35</a></td><td>ALTOVAR:  That's my business.</td></tr>

<tr id="L36"><td><a href="#L36">36</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Oh. I am sorry, but biomemetic gel can be hazardous if handled incorrectly. It's not for sale. At any price.</td></tr>

<tr id="L37"><td><a href="#L37">37</a></td><td>QUARK:  Well, we tried. Thank you, Doctor.</td></tr>

<tr id="L38"><td><a href="#L38">38</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Quark, you might want to warn your friend that even attempting to obtain biomemetic gel is a felony under Federation law.</td></tr>

<tr id="L39"><td><a href="#L39">39</a></td><td>QUARK:  I know. I told him that. But he insisted that I ask you anyway. Letheans can be incredibly stubborn. I hope you'll forgive the interruption.</td></tr>

<tr id="L40"><td><a href="#L40">40</a></td><td>GARAK:  Of course.</td></tr>

<tr id="L41"><td><a href="#L41">41</a></td><td>QUARK:  You know, we just introduced a new lunch menu at the bar.</td></tr>

<tr id="L42"><td><a href="#L42">42</a></td><td>BASHIR:  Goodbye, Quark.</td></tr>

<tr id="L43"><td><a href="#L43">43</a></td><td>GARAK:  Don't take it personally. He's turning thirty.</td></tr>

